      ": 1 ∈ ({1} : Finset ℕ)⟩`. So there are no two distinct elements of `Z` with the same value.\n\nHmm, it seems impossible to have two distinct elements in `Z : Finset α` (as a subtype) with the same `val`, because the subtype is `{x : α // x ∈ s}`, and `s` has no duplicates. \n\nLet me try another example: `α = ℕ × ℕ`, `Z = {(0, 0)}`. Then `Z : Finset (ℕ × ℕ)`, and in `{x : ℕ × ℕ // x ∈ Z}`, there’s only `⟨(0, 0), _⟩`. \n\nBut what if `Z` is `{x : ℕ // x > 0}`? No, because `{x : ℕ // x > 0}` is not a `Finset` unless it is finite. \n\nWait no: in Lean, a `Finset` is always finite by definition. \n\nThus, for any `Z : Finset α`, and `t : Z` (i.e., `t : {x : α // x ∈ Z}`), there cannot be another element in `Z : Finset α` with the same value as `t.val`, because all elements of `Z` are unique. \n\nBut this is false: suppose `Z = {a}`, and `α = {a}/~` where `a ~ a`, then the coercion would not be injective. But in Lean, `Finset` is about finite sets in the usual sense, and if `Z : Finset α`, then all elements in `Z` are distinct as `α`s. \n\nThus, if `t : {x : α // x ∈ Z}`, then for any other `t' : {x : α // x ∈ Z}`, if `t' ≠ t`, then `t'.val ≠ t.val` because `t'.val` and `t.val` are distinct elements of `Z` (as `Finset α`). \n\nThis means that `coerceWord α Z : Word Z → Word α` is injective! \n\nIndeed, suppose `coerceWord α Z w = coerceWord α Z w'`. Then for each letter in `w`, the coercion is the same in `w'`, and because `Z` has no duplicates, the underlying elements must be the same. \n\nBut actually, the `coerceWord` function is just `w.map (fun t => t.val)`, and `t.val` is unique per element of `{x // x ∈ Z}` because no two elements of `{x // x ∈ Z}` have the same `val`. \n\nTherefore, for any `w w' : Word Z`, we have `coerceWord α Z w = coerceWord α Z w'` if and only if `w = w'`. \n\nThus, in the statement `coerceWord α Z w ∈ coerceLang α Z l`, this means that there exists `w' ∈ l` such that `coerceWord α Z w' = coerceWord α Z w`, but because `coerceWord` is